sovereign theft theory and evidence about sovereign default and expropriation siepr siepr stanford institute for economic policy research search the site enter your keywords main links home about siepr research at siepr education at siepr events at siepr people at siepr publications at siepr economics in the news support siepr contact us stay connected stay connected banner home publications profile display sovereign theft theory and evidence about sovereign default and expropriation type scid working paper 400 author s michael tomz mark wright published 09 30 09 abstract this paper examines two major risks to foreign investors default on sovereign debt and expropriation of foreign direct investment which we refer to collectively as sovereign theft using a series of formal models we analyze how the incentives to engage in sovereign theft vary with the state of the economy the risk aversion of political leaders and the nature of punishments for default and expropriation we then document patterns of sovereign theft and foreign investment across much of the twentieth century our research based on a new data set reveals a striking asynchronicity defaults and expropriations have occurred in alternating rather than coincident waves our findings shed new light on the possibility of reputational spillovers across issues and on sources of cooperation and conflict in the international economy full text full text stanford university economics department stanford center for international development public policy program site map economic summit
